________________________________________
Don’t let the IRS take advantage of your hard-earned money. Review your US tax returns with a tax professional.

Some people think that not opening a letter from the IRS somehow magically constitutes not receiving the letter. IRS letters don’t work like that. Once it is in your mailbox, it is being mailed by the IRS. 
What to do when you received a letter from the IRS? You have options: taking care of it on your own (if you are a tax lawyer, an enrolled agent, or a CPA). Another option is to contact an enrolled agent that may save you money on the services provided and take care of your IRS problems on the IRS level (just like a CPA or a tax lawyer represent you on the IRS level). Enrolled agents are licensed to represent taxpayers before the IRS. “Tax lawyer near me” google search will take you to agencies that employ a tax lawyer, a CPA, and an enrolled agent. Tax lawyers can also represent you in tax court. A CPA or an enrolled agent can’t represent you in tax court. Most tax problem cases get resolved on the IRS level and never reach the tax court anyway.

name: Theresa K.
verifications: [('Preferred Freelancer', False), ('Identity Verified', False), ('Payment Verified', False), ('Phone Verified', True), ('Email Verified', True), ('Facebook Connected', False)]
user_description:
My career as an accountant began in 1994 as an Accounts Receivable clerk in a local glass company. I began working in a large CPA firm in 2005 as a full charge bookkeeper for numerous businesses where I quickly transitioned to handling one on one training for clients as well as teaching group QuickBooks classes. I did in-person classes in South Dakota and Wyoming, and I also did a weekly webinar series–way before Zoom was popular! I taught hundreds of bookkeepers and small business owners how to use their QuickBooks more efficiently and to produce financial reports to help manage their business. Almost 17 years ago I saw a need for education and support for business owners and their bookkeepers and I'm still going strong! I moved to a smaller accounting firm in 2013 where I shifted my focus to tax returns but I was still the “go to” person for everything related to QuickBooks in our office. Before the owner's retirement in August 2021, our small firm did 800+ tax returns each year (combined individual and businesses).

Now I do taxes for individuals, corporations and partnerships, consulting, new bookkeeping set up, software conversions, bookkeeping, bank/credit card reconciliations, journal entries, clean up, payroll, sales tax, etc. I am very efficient with QuickBooks and am well known for finding ways to work smarter- not harder. I am also knowledgeable in various other software programs- Accounting CS, T-Value, Microsoft Office, Lacerte, ATX, File Cabinet to name a few. I have year round clients I perform monthly reviews of financial statements and the general ledger. I also have clients I only do year end reviews along with assisting with W2s, year end payroll reporting and 1099s. I make sure that the books aren’t “out of sight – out of mind” once they are presented to the tax preparer. It’s important to see the year end tasks all the way to the end. 

I understand that larger projects take a lot of time. Sometimes billing clients by the hour isn’t ideal and having a fixed rate can assure them that the project isn’t going to put them in the poor house. To assist the owner with budgeting and cash flow purposes for an ongoing engagement, I prefer to do a fixed monthly or quarterly fee based on the needs at the time. We will review the engagement each year to determine if any changes should be made. 

I've been in this industry for almost 30 years and have discovered most people/businesses have anxiety when it comes to their taxes or bookkeeping. Let me help make it less stressful so you can get back to doing the things that you are passionate about. From set up to clean up -- I got you covered!
